1
00:00:02,369 --> 00:00:03,871
(WHOOSHING)

2
00:00:19,553 --> 00:00:22,389
MAN: Mistletoe! Mistletoe!

3
00:00:22,489 --> 00:00:24,391
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

4
00:00:39,239 --> 00:00:40,774
MAN: Come on!

5
00:00:47,915 --> 00:00:49,550
Go on, then.

6
00:00:52,619 --> 00:00:55,188
Warm chestnuts. Chestnuts.

7
00:00:55,289 --> 00:00:58,625
# 0 tidings of comfort and joy

8
00:00:58,725 --> 00:01:00,694
# Comfort and joy
O tidings... #

9
00:01:00,794 --> 00:01:03,497
-You there, boy, what day is this?
-Christmas Eve, sir!

10
00:01:03,597 --> 00:01:05,933
-In what year?
-Are you thick or something?

11
00:01:06,033 --> 00:01:07,701
Oi! Just answer the question!

12
00:01:07,801 --> 00:01:09,937
Year of our Lord, 1851, sir.

13
00:01:10,037 --> 00:01:12,406
Right. Nice year. A bit dull.

14
00:01:12,940 --> 00:01:14,441
WOMAN: Doctor!

15
00:01:16,176 --> 00:01:17,611
Doctor!

16
00:01:18,879 --> 00:01:20,113
Who, me?

17
00:01:21,648 --> 00:01:23,216
Doctor!

18
00:01:23,850 --> 00:01:26,353
Don't worry! Don't worry! Stand back.
What have we got here?

19
00:01:26,453 --> 00:01:27,721
(GROWLING)

20
00:01:27,821 --> 00:01:29,256
Okay, I've got it.
And whatever's behind that door.

21
00:01:29,356 --> 00:01:31,558
-I think you should get out of here.
-Doctor!

22
00:01:31,658 --> 00:01:33,226
No, no, I'm standing right here. Hello.

23
00:01:33,327 --> 00:01:35,295
Don't be so stupid. Who are you?

24
00:01:35,395 --> 00:01:37,097
-I'm the Doctor.
-Doctor who?

25
00:01:37,197 --> 00:01:39,833
-Just the Doctor.
-Well, there can't be two of you!

26
00:01:39,933 --> 00:01:43,270
-Where the hell have you been?
-Right then, don't worry! Stand back.

27
00:01:43,370 --> 00:01:45,172
-What have we got here, then?
-Hold on, who are you?

28
00:01:45,272 --> 00:01:50,611
I'm the Doctor. Simply the Doctor.
The one, the only and the best.

29
00:01:50,711 --> 00:01:52,779
Rosita, give me the sonic screwdriver!

30
00:01:52,879 --> 00:01:54,715
-The what?
-Now, quickly, get back to the Tardis!

31
00:01:54,815 --> 00:01:56,416
-Back to the what?
-If you could stand back, sir,

32
00:01:56,516 --> 00:01:59,019
this is a job for a Time Lord!

33
00:01:59,119 --> 00:02:00,887
Job for a what lord?

34
00:02:02,322 --> 00:02:04,825
-Ooh, that's different!
-Oh, that's new!

35
00:02:04,925 --> 00:02:06,660
BOTH: Allons-y!

36
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:08,929
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

37
00:02:45,832 --> 00:02:47,467
I've been hunting this beast
for a good fortnight.

38
00:02:47,567 --> 00:02:49,936
Now, step back, sir! Oh!

39
00:02:52,139 --> 00:02:55,642
Some sort of primitive conversion,
like they took the brain of a cat

40
00:02:55,742 --> 00:02:58,578
-or a dog.
-Well, talking's all very well. Rosita!

41
00:02:58,679 --> 00:03:01,715
-I'm ready.
-Now, watch and learn.

42
00:03:07,654 --> 00:03:13,160
Excellent! Now then, let's pull
this timorous beastie down to Earth.

43
00:03:13,994 --> 00:03:16,096
(NEXT DOCTOR YELLING)

44
00:03:16,296 --> 00:03:17,297
Or not.

45
00:03:17,397 --> 00:03:19,132
Uh, I might be in a little bit
of trouble.

46
00:03:19,232 --> 00:03:21,501
Nothing changes. I've got you!

47
00:03:22,636 --> 00:03:24,071
(DOCTOR YELLING)

48
00:03:24,171 --> 00:03:25,572
(NEXT DOCTOR YELLING)

49
00:03:25,639 --> 00:03:27,007
You idiots!

50
00:03:29,643 --> 00:03:30,711
Perhaps if you could pull...

51
00:03:30,811 --> 00:03:34,648
I am pulling! In this position,
I couldn't not pull, could I?

52
00:03:38,351 --> 00:03:39,720
Then I suggest you let go, sir!

53
00:03:39,820 --> 00:03:43,056
I'm not letting you out of my sight,
Doctor! Don't you recognise me?

54
00:03:43,156 --> 00:03:45,292
No, should I? Have we met?

55
00:03:45,392 --> 00:03:48,361
This is hardly the right time for me
to go through my social calendar...

56
00:03:53,967 --> 00:03:55,235
Whoa!

57
00:03:57,170 --> 00:03:59,272
(NEXT DOCTOR YELLING)

58
00:04:01,141 --> 00:04:02,275
DOCTOR: Get it!

59
00:04:05,579 --> 00:04:07,047
Get it!

60
00:04:08,615 --> 00:04:11,451
-It's gonna jump!
-We're gonna fall!

61
00:04:19,993 --> 00:04:21,661
(BOTH GROANING)

62
00:04:26,433 --> 00:04:27,701
(LAUGHING)

63
00:04:32,339 --> 00:04:33,874
(BOTH LAUGHING)

64
00:04:40,881 --> 00:04:43,917
Well, I'm glad you think it's so funny!

65
00:04:44,017 --> 00:04:47,154
You're mad! Both of you!
You could've got killed.

66
00:04:47,287 --> 00:04:49,055
But evidently, we did not.

67
00:04:49,156 --> 00:04:53,026
Oh, I should introduce Rosita,
my faithful companion.

68
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:56,763
-Always telling me off.
-Well, they do, don't they? Rosita.

69
00:04:57,898 --> 00:05:00,100
Good name. Hello, Rosita.

70
00:05:00,167 --> 00:05:01,201
(SCOFFING)

71
00:05:01,301 --> 00:05:04,838
Now I'll have to go and dismantle
the traps! All of that for nothing!

72
00:05:04,938 --> 00:05:08,542
And we've only got 20 minutes
till the funeral, don't forget.

73
00:05:08,642 --> 00:05:10,510
ROSITA: Then back to the Tardis, right?

74
00:05:10,610 --> 00:05:14,214
-Funeral?
-Oh, long story. Not my own, not yet.

75
00:05:15,015 --> 00:05:16,550
(GROANING)

76
00:05:16,650 --> 00:05:17,984
I'm not as young as I was.

77
00:05:18,084 --> 00:05:20,187
Well, not as young as you were
when you were me.

78
00:05:20,287 --> 00:05:22,522
When I was who?

79
00:05:22,622 --> 00:05:25,659
-You really don't recognise me?
-Not at all.

80
00:05:25,759 --> 00:05:28,995
But you're the Doctor. The next Doctor.

81
00:05:29,863 --> 00:05:31,665
Or the next-but-one.
A future Doctor anyway.

82
00:05:31,765 --> 00:05:34,100
-Oh.
-No, no, don't tell me how it happened.

83
00:05:34,201 --> 00:05:36,870
Although I hope I don't just trip
over a brick.

84
00:05:36,970 --> 00:05:40,307
That'd be embarrassing.
Then again, painless. Worse ways to go.

85
00:05:40,407 --> 00:05:41,441
Depends on the brick.

86
00:05:41,541 --> 00:05:46,112
You're gabbling, sir. Now, might I ask,
who are you exactly?

87
00:05:48,915 --> 00:05:52,752
No, I'm, uh, I'm just... Smith.
John Smith.

88
00:05:52,853 --> 00:05:57,757
But I've heard all about you, Doctor.
Bit of a legend if I say so myself.

89
00:05:57,858 --> 00:06:01,695
Modesty forbids me to agree
with you, sir. But yes. Yes, I am.

90
00:06:02,128 --> 00:06:05,932
A legend with certain memories missing.
Am I right?

91
00:06:06,032 --> 00:06:07,434
How do you know that?

92
00:06:07,534 --> 00:06:09,302
You've forgotten me.

93
00:06:10,837 --> 00:06:14,975
Great swathes of my life have been
stolen away. When I turn my mind

94
00:06:15,075 --> 00:06:18,011
to the past...there's nothing.

95
00:06:18,411 --> 00:06:21,481
-Going how far back?
-Since the Cybermen.

96
00:06:21,581 --> 00:06:23,683
Masters of that hellish wall-scuttler,

97
00:06:23,783 --> 00:06:27,120
and old enemies of mine,
now at work in London Town.

98
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:32,025
You won't believe this, Mr Smith, but
they are creatures from another world.

99
00:06:32,125 --> 00:06:34,394
Really? Wow.

100
00:06:34,928 --> 00:06:39,165
It is said they fell onto London.
Out of the sky in a blaze of light.

101
00:06:41,801 --> 00:06:43,570
And they found me.

102
00:06:49,009 --> 00:06:50,644
Something was taken.

103
00:06:51,811 --> 00:06:53,780
And something was lost.

104
00:06:55,649 --> 00:06:57,317
What was I like?

105
00:06:57,918 --> 00:06:59,352
In the past?

106
00:07:00,453 --> 00:07:03,323
Well, I don't think I should say. Sorry.

107
00:07:03,423 --> 00:07:05,425
Got to be careful with memory loss.
One wrong word...

108
00:07:05,525 --> 00:07:10,196
It's strange, though.
I talk of Cybermen from the stars

109
00:07:11,698 --> 00:07:13,733
and you don't blink, Mr Smith.

110
00:07:13,833 --> 00:07:17,037
Ah, don't blink, remember that?
Whatever you do, don't blink.

111
00:07:17,137 --> 00:07:20,974
The blinking and the statues
with Sally and the angels. No?

112
00:07:21,374 --> 00:07:23,209
You're a very odd man.

113
00:07:23,843 --> 00:07:25,478
Mmm, I still am.

114
00:07:26,246 --> 00:07:27,681
Something's wrong here.

115
00:07:27,781 --> 00:07:31,985
Oh, the funeral! The funeral's at 2:00!
It's been a pleasure, Mr Smith.

116
00:07:32,252 --> 00:07:34,521
-Don't breathe a word of it.
-Oh, can't I come with you?

117
00:07:34,621 --> 00:07:38,191
Oh, it's far too dangerous! Rest
assured, I shall keep this city safe.

118
00:07:38,291 --> 00:07:41,962
Oh, and, uh, merry Christmas, Mr Smith.

119
00:07:42,062 --> 00:07:43,997
Merry Christmas, Doctor.

120
00:07:49,769 --> 00:07:51,638
(MECHANICAL FOOTSTEPS)

121
00:07:55,942 --> 00:07:57,043
Report.

122
00:07:57,143 --> 00:07:59,512
Cybershade 16 has made contact.

123
00:08:00,046 --> 00:08:02,015
Then observe the enemy.

124
00:08:02,382 --> 00:08:04,351
This man is dangerous.

125
00:08:04,451 --> 00:08:08,722
This man is our enemy.
This man is the Doctor.

126
00:08:08,822 --> 00:08:10,357
I've been hunting this beast
for a good fortnight.

127
00:08:10,457 --> 00:08:12,592
NEXT DOCTOR: Now, step back, sir!

128
00:08:12,692 --> 00:08:16,296
The attack is scheduled
for 1400 hours. Plans for the Ascension

129
00:08:16,396 --> 00:08:20,400
demand a successful intervention.
Is everything in position?

130
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:24,637
That's rather dependent on you.
Alll can promise is to do my best.

131
00:08:24,738 --> 00:08:27,207
Define the parameters of "best".

132
00:08:27,774 --> 00:08:31,878
As you would say, I will operate
at maximum efficiency.

133
00:08:32,746 --> 00:08:34,347
And you'll keep your part
of the bargain?

134
00:08:34,447 --> 00:08:38,952
You will be heralded in the new age
at the court of the CyberKing.

135
00:08:39,052 --> 00:08:41,287
QYBERMEN: The CyberKing will rise.

136
00:08:41,454 --> 00:08:45,291
The CyberKing will rise...indeed.

137
00:08:46,292 --> 00:08:47,794
How like a man.

138
00:08:48,995 --> 00:08:51,464
Now, if you'll excuse me,

139
00:08:51,564 --> 00:08:53,533
I have a funeral to attend.

140
00:08:53,633 --> 00:08:55,301
(BELL TOLLING)

141
00:09:03,410 --> 00:09:06,379
The late Reverend Fairchild
leaving his place of residence

142
00:09:06,479 --> 00:09:08,248
for the last time.

143
00:09:09,482 --> 00:09:11,785
NEXT DOCTOR: God rest his soul.

144
00:09:12,852 --> 00:09:16,723
Now, with the house empty,
I shall effect an entrance at the rear,

145
00:09:16,823 --> 00:09:21,294
while you go back to the Tardis.
This is hardly work for a woman.

146
00:09:22,195 --> 00:09:25,265
Don't mind me saving your life!
That's work for a woman, isn't it?

147
00:09:25,365 --> 00:09:29,102
The Doctor's companion does what
the Doctor says. Off you go.

148
00:09:41,714 --> 00:09:44,117
-Hello.
-But...how did you get in?

149
00:09:44,217 --> 00:09:47,887
Oh, front door. I'm good at doors.
Um, do you mind my asking?

150
00:09:48,354 --> 00:09:50,857
-Is that your sonic screwdriver?
-Yes.

151
00:09:50,957 --> 00:09:52,559
I'd be lost without it.

152
00:09:52,659 --> 00:09:54,594
But that's a screwdriver.

153
00:09:55,261 --> 00:09:56,996
How is it sonic?

154
00:09:57,097 --> 00:09:59,332
Well, uh, it makes a noise.

155
00:09:59,899 --> 00:10:03,103
That's sonic, isn't it? Now,
since we're acting like common burglars,

156
00:10:03,203 --> 00:10:05,738
I suggest we get out of plain view.

157
00:10:09,976 --> 00:10:12,312
This investigation of yours,
what's it all about?

158
00:10:12,412 --> 00:10:15,582
-It started with a murder.
-Oh, good.

159
00:10:16,883 --> 00:10:18,885
I mean, bad. But whose?

160
00:10:18,985 --> 00:10:22,322
Mr Jackson Lake. A teacher
of mathematics from Sussex.

161
00:10:22,422 --> 00:10:26,559
He came to London three weeks ago,
and died a terrible death.

162
00:10:26,659 --> 00:10:28,361
Cybermen?

163
00:10:28,461 --> 00:10:32,265
It's hard to say. His body was
never found. But then it started.

164
00:10:32,365 --> 00:10:35,301
More secret murders. Then abductions.

165
00:10:35,401 --> 00:10:38,738
Children...stolen away in silence.

166
00:10:39,806 --> 00:10:41,307
So, whose house is this?

167
00:10:41,407 --> 00:10:44,644
The latest murder.
The Reverend Aubrey Fairchild.

168
00:10:44,744 --> 00:10:49,015
Found with burns to his forehead, like
some advanced form of electrocution.

169
00:10:49,115 --> 00:10:50,817
But who was he? Was he important?

170
00:10:50,917 --> 00:10:52,318
You ask a lot of questions.

171
00:10:52,418 --> 00:10:54,120
I'm your companion!

172
00:10:54,821 --> 00:10:57,624
The Reverend was the pillar
of the community.

173
00:10:57,724 --> 00:11:01,261
A member of many parish boards.
A keen advocate of children's charities.

174
00:11:01,361 --> 00:11:02,462
Children again.

175
00:11:02,562 --> 00:11:04,797
But why would the Cybermen
want him dead?

176
00:11:04,898 --> 00:11:08,735
And what's his connection
to the first death, this Jackson Lake?

177
00:11:09,602 --> 00:11:10,937
It's funny.

178
00:11:11,838 --> 00:11:14,440
I seem to be telling you everything

179
00:11:15,542 --> 00:11:19,078
as though you engendered
some sort of...trust.

180
00:11:20,914 --> 00:11:23,183
You seem familiar, Mr Smith.

181
00:11:24,050 --> 00:11:25,685
I know your face.

182
00:11:26,786 --> 00:11:28,121
But how?

183
00:11:28,888 --> 00:11:33,826
I wonder. I can't help noticing
you're wearing a fob watch.

184
00:11:35,562 --> 00:11:37,564
Is that important?

185
00:11:37,664 --> 00:11:41,568
Legend has it that the memories
of a Time Lord can be contained

186
00:11:41,634 --> 00:11:43,203
within a watch.

187
00:11:44,337 --> 00:11:45,805
Do you mind?

188
00:11:46,839 --> 00:11:48,708
(WHISPERING VOICES)

189
00:11:48,808 --> 00:11:51,544
It's said that if it's opened...

190
00:11:54,614 --> 00:11:56,950
Oh. Maybe not.

191
00:11:57,050 --> 00:12:00,420
-It's more for decoration.
-Yeah, anyway. Alien infiltration.

192
00:12:00,520 --> 00:12:03,156
Yes, just look for anything different,
possibly metal.

193
00:12:03,256 --> 00:12:04,424
Anything that doesn't seem to belong.

194
00:12:04,524 --> 00:12:07,594
Perhaps a mechanical device
that could fit no earthly engine.

195
00:12:07,694 --> 00:12:10,363
Could even seem to be organic,
but unlike any organism

196
00:12:10,463 --> 00:12:11,731
of the natural world.

197
00:12:11,798 --> 00:12:13,099
Shh!

198
00:12:13,199 --> 00:12:14,634
What's that noise?

199
00:12:14,734 --> 00:12:18,338
Oh, it's just me. Whistling.

200
00:12:21,774 --> 00:12:24,143
I wonder what's in here, though.

201
00:12:25,812 --> 00:12:27,080
Ah.

202
00:12:28,081 --> 00:12:30,116
Different and metal. You were right.

203
00:12:30,216 --> 00:12:32,919
They are info stamps.

204
00:12:33,419 --> 00:12:36,823
I mean, at a guess. Uh, if I were you,

205
00:12:36,923 --> 00:12:39,859
I'd say they worked something like this.

206
00:12:42,562 --> 00:12:45,932
See? Compressed information. Tons of it.

207
00:12:47,367 --> 00:12:52,005
That is the history of London,
1066 to the present day.

208
00:12:52,605 --> 00:12:54,741
This thing's like a disc, a cyberdisc.

209
00:12:54,841 --> 00:12:58,678
But why would the Cybermen
need something so simple?

210
00:12:58,945 --> 00:13:00,813
They've gotta be wireless.

211
00:13:02,215 --> 00:13:05,018
Unless they're in the wrong century.

212
00:13:05,118 --> 00:13:08,554
They haven't got much power.
They need plain, old, basic info stamps

213
00:13:08,655 --> 00:13:09,856
to update themselves.

214
00:13:09,956 --> 00:13:11,357
Are you all right?

215
00:13:11,457 --> 00:13:13,059
I'm fine.

216
00:13:13,159 --> 00:13:15,662
No, what is it? What's wrong?

217
00:13:16,095 --> 00:13:18,331
I've seen one of these before.

218
00:13:23,202 --> 00:13:26,205
I was holding this device

219
00:13:27,206 --> 00:13:29,142
the night I lost my mind.

220
00:13:30,410 --> 00:13:32,478
The night I regenerated.

221
00:13:39,452 --> 00:13:42,088
The Cybermen, they made me change.

222
00:13:42,622 --> 00:13:44,724
My mind. My face. My whole self.

223
00:13:46,659 --> 00:13:48,461
And you were there.

224
00:13:49,329 --> 00:13:50,596
Who are you?

225
00:13:50,697 --> 00:13:51,964
A friend.

226
00:13:52,565 --> 00:13:53,900
I swear.

227
00:13:54,400 --> 00:13:57,236
Then I beg you, John, help me.

228
00:13:57,837 --> 00:13:58,938
Ah.

229
00:13:59,439 --> 00:14:01,240
Two words I never refuse.

230
00:14:03,576 --> 00:14:05,378
But it's not a conversation
for a dead man's house.

231
00:14:05,478 --> 00:14:07,313
It'll make more sense
if we go back to the Tardis.

232
00:14:07,413 --> 00:14:11,517
Your, uh, Tardis. Hold on, I just need
to do a little final check.

233
00:14:11,617 --> 00:14:14,354
Won't take a tick, 'cause there's
one more thing I can't help thinking.

234
00:14:14,454 --> 00:14:17,957
If this room's got info stamps,
then maybe, just maybe,

235
00:14:18,057 --> 00:14:20,493
it's got something
that needs infostamping.

236
00:14:21,127 --> 00:14:22,562
Okay.

237
00:14:22,662 --> 00:14:24,697
I think we should run.

238
00:14:24,797 --> 00:14:26,499
Run, Doctor. Now, Doctor!

239
00:14:26,566 --> 00:14:27,800
Delete.

240
00:14:31,204 --> 00:14:33,139
The Doctor will be deleted.

241
00:14:34,841 --> 00:14:35,942
Delete.

242
00:14:36,042 --> 00:14:38,611
Stairs! Can't lead him outside!

243
00:14:45,418 --> 00:14:46,686
Delete.

244
00:14:47,854 --> 00:14:50,256
I'm a dab hand with a cutlass.
You don't want to come near me

245
00:14:50,356 --> 00:14:52,925
when I've got one of these.
This is your last warning.

246
00:14:53,025 --> 00:14:56,095
No? Okay, this is really
your last warning! Okay, I give up.

247
00:14:56,195 --> 00:14:57,663
-Delete.
-Listen to me properly!

248
00:14:57,764 --> 00:15:00,800
Whatever you're doing, stuck in 1851,
I can help! I mean it!

249
00:15:00,900 --> 00:15:02,702
I'm the only person in the world
who can help you!

250
00:15:02,802 --> 00:15:04,704
-Listen to me!
-Delete.

251
00:15:04,804 --> 00:15:08,541
I'm the Doctor! You need me!
Check your memory banks.

252
00:15:08,641 --> 00:15:11,277
My name is the Doctor!
Leave this man alone!

253
00:15:11,377 --> 00:15:13,045
The Doctor is me!

254
00:15:14,213 --> 00:15:15,348
Delete.

255
00:15:16,182 --> 00:15:17,817
The Doctor, remember?

256
00:15:17,917 --> 00:15:20,620
I'm the Doctor! You need me alive.

257
00:15:20,720 --> 00:15:23,256
You need the Doctor, and that's me!

258
00:15:27,360 --> 00:15:28,895
(DOCTOR GRUNTING)

259
00:15:29,262 --> 00:15:30,496
Delete.

260
00:15:46,212 --> 00:15:48,981
Infostamp with a cyclo-Steinham core.

261
00:15:49,081 --> 00:15:51,317
You ripped open the core
and broke the safety. Zap!

262
00:15:51,417 --> 00:15:52,785
(CHUCKLING)

263
00:15:52,885 --> 00:15:54,720
Only the Doctor would think of that.

264
00:15:54,821 --> 00:15:56,189
I did that.

265
00:15:57,323 --> 00:15:58,758
Last time.

266
00:15:59,325 --> 00:16:01,360
Come here. You'll be okay.

267
00:16:01,961 --> 00:16:03,729
Let me just check.

268
00:16:04,163 --> 00:16:06,599
You told them you were the Doctor.
Why did you do that?

269
00:16:06,699 --> 00:16:09,101
Oh, I was just protecting you.

270
00:16:09,202 --> 00:16:12,939
You're trying to take away
the only thing I've got. Like they did.

271
00:16:13,039 --> 00:16:16,409
They stole something.
Something so precious.

272
00:16:18,277 --> 00:16:23,149
But I can't remember.
What happened to me? What did they do?

273
00:16:23,249 --> 00:16:26,319
We'll find out. You and me, together.

274
00:16:30,490 --> 00:16:33,593
VICAR: Forasmuch as it hath pleased
Almighty God of his great mercy,

275
00:16:33,693 --> 00:16:37,196
to take unto Himself the soul
of our dear brother here departed,

276
00:16:37,296 --> 00:16:39,866
we therefore commit his body
to the ground.

277
00:16:39,966 --> 00:16:44,136
Earth to earth, ashes to ashes
and dust to dust,

278
00:16:44,237 --> 00:16:47,740
in sure and certain hope
of the Resurrection to eternal life

279
00:16:47,840 --> 00:16:50,042
through our Lord Jesus Christ,

280
00:16:51,177 --> 00:16:54,647
who shall change our vile body

281
00:16:54,747 --> 00:16:59,085
that it may be like
unto his glorious body,

282
00:16:59,185 --> 00:17:01,621
according to the mighty working...

283
00:17:02,889 --> 00:17:04,724
Do continue.

284
00:17:04,824 --> 00:17:07,093
Madam, I must protest!

285
00:17:07,159 --> 00:17:08,261
Whatever for?

286
00:17:08,361 --> 00:17:10,963
A lady at the graveside is
debatable enough,

287
00:17:11,063 --> 00:17:13,366
but your apparel!

288
00:17:13,466 --> 00:17:14,700
Is it too exciting?

289
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:17,537
You're disgracing the ceremony!
Dressed like a harlot!

290
00:17:17,637 --> 00:17:21,073
-Oh, and you should know, Mr Cole.
-How do you know my name?

291
00:17:21,173 --> 00:17:26,178
You've walked past me so many times,
all you good men of charity.

292
00:17:26,646 --> 00:17:28,548
Never once asking my name.

293
00:17:28,648 --> 00:17:30,816
It's Miss Hartigan, isn't it?

294
00:17:30,917 --> 00:17:35,221
Oh, you noticed. I saw you looking,
you cheeky boy.

295
00:17:36,722 --> 00:17:39,926
-I'm sorry, but who is she?
-Matron of the St Joseph Workhouse.

296
00:17:40,026 --> 00:17:41,894
Your humble servant.

297
00:17:42,762 --> 00:17:45,231
Oh, I've watched you all visiting.

298
00:17:45,331 --> 00:17:49,635
Smiling. Bestowing your beneficence
upon the poor,

299
00:17:49,735 --> 00:17:51,704
while I scrubbed down their filthy beds.

300
00:17:51,804 --> 00:17:54,407
I must insist that you depart.

301
00:17:54,507 --> 00:17:57,977
But that's why the late
Reverend Fairchild had to die.

302
00:17:59,178 --> 00:18:02,949
To gather you all in one place.
Where better than a funeral?

303
00:18:03,583 --> 00:18:06,919
Man that is born of woman hath
but a short time to live.

304
00:18:07,019 --> 00:18:10,389
Although I've got some friends
who might disagree with that.

305
00:18:10,489 --> 00:18:12,391
Would you like to meet them?

306
00:18:12,491 --> 00:18:15,361
Hark! I can hear them now.

307
00:18:16,128 --> 00:18:18,130
(MECHANICAL FOOTSTEPS)

308
00:18:20,800 --> 00:18:22,735
(MEN MUTTERING)

309
00:18:49,929 --> 00:18:54,667
Mr Cole, Mr Scoones, Mr Fetch,
Mr Milligan, stay where you are.

310
00:18:54,767 --> 00:18:59,672
You're needed.
The rest of you are disposable. Sorry.

311
00:18:59,772 --> 00:19:01,841
What manner of men are they?

312
00:19:02,408 --> 00:19:03,609
Cybermen.

313
00:19:03,709 --> 00:19:04,744
(GROWLING)

314
00:19:04,844 --> 00:19:07,146
-Save yourselves!
-Quickly! Get away from me!

315
00:19:07,246 --> 00:19:08,981
(ALL YELLING)

316
00:19:23,663 --> 00:19:26,432
I repeat, Mr Cole, Mr Scoones, Mr Fetch,

317
00:19:26,532 --> 00:19:29,068
Mr Milligan, stay!

318
00:19:54,493 --> 00:19:56,328
You monstrous witch!

319
00:19:56,429 --> 00:19:58,230
Merry Christmas to you, too.

320
00:19:58,330 --> 00:20:01,567
But why are we spared?
What do you need us for?

321
00:20:01,667 --> 00:20:03,402
Your children.

322
00:20:03,502 --> 00:20:07,440
It's funny, now I think of it,
but in all these years, not one of you

323
00:20:07,540 --> 00:20:09,508
has asked my first name.

324
00:20:11,577 --> 00:20:13,012
It's Mercy.

325
00:20:16,615 --> 00:20:18,250
Doctor!

326
00:20:18,350 --> 00:20:20,352
-I thought you were dead!
-Oh!

327
00:20:20,453 --> 00:20:22,955
Now then, Rosita. A little decorum.

328
00:20:23,055 --> 00:20:24,623
You've been gone for so long.

329
00:20:24,724 --> 00:20:28,527
He's always doing this.
Leaving me behind. Going frantic.

330
00:20:28,627 --> 00:20:32,264
-What about the Tardis?
-Oh, she's ready. Come on.

331
00:20:32,364 --> 00:20:34,400
I'm looking forward to this.

332
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,203
You were right, though, Rosita.

333
00:20:37,336 --> 00:20:40,506
The Reverend Fairchild's death
was the work of the Cybermen.

334
00:20:40,606 --> 00:20:42,074
So, you live here?

335
00:20:42,174 --> 00:20:45,044
A temporary base
until we rout the enemy.

336
00:20:45,845 --> 00:20:48,147
The Tardis is magnificent,
but it's hardly a home.

337
00:20:48,247 --> 00:20:50,483
And where's the Tardis now?

338
00:20:50,583 --> 00:20:51,984
In the yard.

339
00:20:53,619 --> 00:20:55,554
Um, what's all this luggage?

340
00:20:55,654 --> 00:20:59,892
Evidence. The property of Jackson Lake,
the first man to be murdered.

341
00:21:01,060 --> 00:21:05,164
Oh, but my new friend is a fighter,
Rosita, much like myself.

342
00:21:05,264 --> 00:21:08,000
He faced the Cybermen with a cutlass.

343
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:12,138
I'm not ashamed to say
he was braver than I.

344
00:21:13,973 --> 00:21:15,941
He was quite brilliant.

345
00:21:18,444 --> 00:21:20,412
Are you whistling again?

346
00:21:21,180 --> 00:21:23,883
Yes. Yes, I am. Yeah. Yeah.

347
00:21:32,124 --> 00:21:36,362
-That's another man's property.
-Well, a dead man's.

348
00:21:38,731 --> 00:21:40,566
How did you two meet, then?

349
00:21:40,666 --> 00:21:42,301
He saved my life.

350
00:21:43,869 --> 00:21:46,539
Late one night by the Osterman's Wharf,

351
00:21:47,039 --> 00:21:50,743
this creature came out of the shadows.

352
00:21:51,944 --> 00:21:53,746
A man made of metal.

353
00:21:55,948 --> 00:21:58,951
I thought I was going to die. And then

354
00:22:00,186 --> 00:22:01,620
there he was.

355
00:22:02,388 --> 00:22:03,823
The Doctor.

356
00:22:06,292 --> 00:22:08,093
Can you help him, sir?

357
00:22:08,661 --> 00:22:10,796
He has such terrible dreams.

358
00:22:10,896 --> 00:22:14,266
Wakes at night
in such a state of terror.

359
00:22:14,733 --> 00:22:16,368
Come now, Rosita.

360
00:22:17,169 --> 00:22:19,305
With all the things a Time Lord
has seen,

361
00:22:19,405 --> 00:22:23,108
everything he's lost,
he may surely have bad dreams.

362
00:22:24,543 --> 00:22:25,644
Yeah.

363
00:22:30,082 --> 00:22:32,551
Oh, now, look.

364
00:22:34,720 --> 00:22:36,689
Jackson Lake had an info stamp.

365
00:22:36,789 --> 00:22:39,425
But how? Is that significant?

366
00:22:39,892 --> 00:22:44,496
Doctor, the answer to all this is
in your Tardis. Could I see it?

367
00:22:44,763 --> 00:22:46,565
Mr Smith, it would be my honour.

368
00:22:51,704 --> 00:22:53,105
There she is.

369
00:22:53,739 --> 00:22:56,308
My transport through time and space.

370
00:22:58,310 --> 00:23:00,145
NEXT DOCTOR: The Tardis!

371
00:23:00,246 --> 00:23:02,081
You've got a balloon.

372
00:23:03,649 --> 00:23:06,518
Tardis. T-A-R-D-I-S.

373
00:23:06,619 --> 00:23:11,056
It stands for Tethered Aerial Release
Developed in Style. Do you see?

374
00:23:12,725 --> 00:23:14,426
Well, I do now.

375
00:23:15,427 --> 00:23:18,297
I like it. Good Tardis!

376
00:23:20,065 --> 00:23:23,202
Brilliant. Nice one.
And it's inflated by gas, yeah?

377
00:23:23,302 --> 00:23:25,371
We're adjacent
to the Mutton Street Gasworks.

378
00:23:25,471 --> 00:23:27,840
I pay them a modest fee. Good work, Jed!

379
00:23:27,940 --> 00:23:30,009
Glad to be of service, sir.

380
00:23:32,111 --> 00:23:33,679
You've got quite a bit of money.

381
00:23:33,779 --> 00:23:35,915
Oh, you get nothing for nothing.

382
00:23:36,015 --> 00:23:38,951
-How's that ripped panel, Jed?
-All repaired. Should work a treat.

383
00:23:39,051 --> 00:23:42,021
Never know, maybe tonight's
the night, Doctor.

384
00:23:42,121 --> 00:23:45,257
Imagine it, seeing Christmas from above.

385
00:23:47,626 --> 00:23:52,665
Not just yet, I think.
One day I will ascend. One day soon.

386
00:23:54,700 --> 00:23:56,435
You've never actually been up?

387
00:23:56,535 --> 00:23:59,438
He dreams of leaving, but never does.

388
00:23:59,538 --> 00:24:03,242
I can depart in the Tardis
once London is safe.

389
00:24:04,977 --> 00:24:08,814
And finally, when I'm up there...
Think of it, John.

390
00:24:10,082 --> 00:24:11,951
The time and the space.

391
00:24:13,352 --> 00:24:15,054
The perfect escape.

392
00:24:17,923 --> 00:24:20,926
Do you ever wonder
what you're escaping from?

393
00:24:21,927 --> 00:24:23,929
With every moment.

394
00:24:24,029 --> 00:24:26,332
Then do you want me to tell you?

395
00:24:27,099 --> 00:24:29,768
'Cause I think I've worked it out now.

396
00:24:30,536 --> 00:24:32,604
How you became the Doctor.

397
00:24:33,706 --> 00:24:35,441
What do you think?

398
00:24:36,342 --> 00:24:38,043
Do you want to know?

399
00:24:41,480 --> 00:24:44,483
Mr Cole, Mr Scoones, Mr Fetch
and Mr Milligan,

400
00:24:45,551 --> 00:24:49,321
you have your instructions and
the court of the CyberKing is waiting.

401
00:24:49,421 --> 00:24:52,424
But first of all, let's just see.

402
00:24:52,491 --> 00:24:53,993
A little test.

403
00:24:54,626 --> 00:24:56,028
Turn right.

404
00:24:57,830 --> 00:24:59,264
Turn left.

405
00:25:01,333 --> 00:25:03,168
And face me.

406
00:25:03,268 --> 00:25:04,837
(CHUCKLING)

407
00:25:04,937 --> 00:25:10,209
Oh, I could do this forever.
But now, set about your appointed tasks.

408
00:25:11,577 --> 00:25:13,379
And bring them to me.

409
00:25:19,051 --> 00:25:21,553
(HORSE NEIGHING)

410
00:25:26,492 --> 00:25:29,328
The story begins with the Cybermen.

411
00:25:29,428 --> 00:25:31,063
A long time away,

412
00:25:31,163 --> 00:25:34,466
and not so far from here,
the Cybermen were fought,

413
00:25:35,868 --> 00:25:38,170
and they were beaten,
and they were sent into

414
00:25:38,270 --> 00:25:43,008
a howling wilderness called the Void,
locked inside for evermore.

415
00:25:43,709 --> 00:25:45,978
But then a greater battle rose up,

416
00:25:46,912 --> 00:25:50,249
so great that everything
inside the Void perished.

417
00:25:50,849 --> 00:25:54,153
But as the walls of the world weakened,

418
00:25:54,253 --> 00:25:57,489
the last of the Cybermen must have
fallen through the dimensions,

419
00:25:57,589 --> 00:26:02,428
back in time, to land here.
Then they found you.

420
00:26:02,528 --> 00:26:04,696
I fought them. I know that.

421
00:26:05,831 --> 00:26:07,232
But what happened?

422
00:26:07,332 --> 00:26:10,469
At the same time,
another man came to London.

423
00:26:10,569 --> 00:26:12,171
Mr Jackson Lake.

424
00:26:12,938 --> 00:26:16,008
Plenty of luggage. Money in his pocket.

425
00:26:16,108 --> 00:26:19,611
Maybe coming to town
for the winter season, I don't know.

426
00:26:20,112 --> 00:26:22,381
But he found the Cybermen, too.

427
00:26:23,282 --> 00:26:26,285
And just like you, exactly like you,

428
00:26:28,053 --> 00:26:30,189
he took hold of an info stamp.

429
00:26:31,023 --> 00:26:34,993
But he's dead. Jackson Lake is dead.
The Cybermen murdered him.

430
00:26:35,094 --> 00:26:37,429
You said no body was ever found.

431
00:26:38,130 --> 00:26:40,265
And you kept all his suitcases,
but you could never bring yourself

432
00:26:40,365 --> 00:26:41,834
to open them.

433
00:26:43,802 --> 00:26:46,338
I told you the answer was
in the fob watch.

434
00:26:48,006 --> 00:26:49,241
Can I see?

435
00:27:05,891 --> 00:27:08,060
The watch is Jackson Lake's.

436
00:27:09,728 --> 00:27:12,464
Jackson Lake is you, sir?

437
00:27:14,566 --> 00:27:16,301
But I'm the Doctor.

438
00:27:18,137 --> 00:27:22,908
You became the Doctor
because the info stamp you picked up

439
00:27:23,008 --> 00:27:25,544
was a book about one particular man.

440
00:27:28,113 --> 00:27:30,182
DOCTOR: The Cybermen's database.

441
00:27:32,551 --> 00:27:34,686
Stolen from the Daleks inside the Void,
I'd say.

442
00:27:34,786 --> 00:27:38,991
But it's everything you could want
to know about the Doctor.

443
00:27:43,562 --> 00:27:45,164
JACKSON: That's you.

444
00:27:46,331 --> 00:27:48,534
Time Lord. Tardis.
Enemy of the Cybermen.

445
00:27:48,634 --> 00:27:50,202
(CLICKING TONGUE)

446
00:27:50,536 --> 00:27:52,371
The one and the only.

447
00:27:55,340 --> 00:27:58,944
You see, the info stamp must
have backfired.

448
00:28:00,312 --> 00:28:05,050
Streamed all that information
about me right inside your head.

449
00:28:22,267 --> 00:28:23,969
I am nothing but a lie.

450
00:28:24,069 --> 00:28:27,806
No, no, no, no, no.
Infostamps are just facts and figures.

451
00:28:28,307 --> 00:28:29,942
All that bravery.

452
00:28:30,409 --> 00:28:32,945
Saving Rosita. Defending London Town.

453
00:28:33,612 --> 00:28:34,846
Mmm?

454
00:28:34,947 --> 00:28:37,649
And the invention,
building a Tardis, that's all you.

455
00:28:38,217 --> 00:28:39,685
And what else?

456
00:28:42,588 --> 00:28:44,289
Tell me what else.

457
00:28:45,791 --> 00:28:47,593
There's still something missing,
isn't there?

458
00:28:47,693 --> 00:28:49,828
I demand you tell me, sir!

459
00:28:50,495 --> 00:28:52,464
Tell me what they took!

460
00:28:56,468 --> 00:28:57,603
Sorry.

461
00:28:59,271 --> 00:29:01,139
Really, I am so sorry.

462
00:29:03,609 --> 00:29:06,645
But that's an awful lot of luggage
for one man.

463
00:29:09,448 --> 00:29:11,083
'Cause an info stamp is plain technology.

464
00:29:11,183 --> 00:29:14,052
It's not enough to make
a man lose his mind.

465
00:29:14,686 --> 00:29:17,256
What you suffered is called a fugue.

466
00:29:18,824 --> 00:29:20,292
A fugue state.

467
00:29:21,193 --> 00:29:25,163
Where the mind just runs away
because it can't bear to look back.

468
00:29:27,733 --> 00:29:30,135
You wanted to become someone else

469
00:29:31,770 --> 00:29:34,373
because Jackson Lake had lost so much.

470
00:29:36,341 --> 00:29:37,943
(BELL TOLLING)

471
00:29:38,977 --> 00:29:40,345
Midnight.

472
00:29:41,246 --> 00:29:42,748
Christmas Day.

473
00:29:45,651 --> 00:29:46,952
I remember.

474
00:29:50,422 --> 00:29:52,024
Oh, my God.

475
00:29:55,661 --> 00:29:57,029
No!

476
00:29:57,095 --> 00:29:58,363
Caroline!

477
00:29:58,463 --> 00:29:59,831
(BOTH YELLING)

478
00:30:01,733 --> 00:30:03,168
Caroline.

479
00:30:08,273 --> 00:30:10,008
They killed my wife.

480
00:30:14,613 --> 00:30:16,214
They killed her.

481
00:30:19,418 --> 00:30:22,020
(BEEPING)

482
00:30:33,932 --> 00:30:35,567
(LOUD BEEPING)

483
00:30:37,336 --> 00:30:38,670
Oh.

484
00:30:39,805 --> 00:30:41,907
You found a whole cache of info stamps.

485
00:30:42,007 --> 00:30:44,810
But what is it? What's that noise?

486
00:30:44,910 --> 00:30:48,447
Activation. A call to arms.
The Cybermen are moving!

487
00:31:00,392 --> 00:31:02,294
The Doctor needs help.

488
00:31:03,228 --> 00:31:05,464
I learnt that much about him.

489
00:31:05,764 --> 00:31:08,066
There should be someone at his side.

490
00:31:08,567 --> 00:31:09,868
Now, go.

491
00:31:11,002 --> 00:31:12,137
Go.

492
00:31:23,348 --> 00:31:25,450
What is it? What's happening?

493
00:31:31,890 --> 00:31:35,594
That's Mr Cole. He's master
of the Hazel Street Workhouse.

494
00:31:35,694 --> 00:31:39,431
-Maybe he's taking them to prayers.
-No, nothing as holy as that.

495
00:31:39,531 --> 00:31:41,099
Can you hear me?

496
00:31:41,533 --> 00:31:42,734
Hello?

497
00:31:43,735 --> 00:31:44,903
No?

498
00:31:45,270 --> 00:31:47,973
Mr Cole, you seem to have something
in your ear.

499
00:31:48,073 --> 00:31:50,108
Now, this might hurt a bit,
but if I can just...

500
00:31:50,208 --> 00:31:51,443
(GROWLING)

501
00:31:52,577 --> 00:31:56,114
They're on guard. Can't risk a fight.
Not with the children.

502
00:31:56,214 --> 00:31:57,449
But where are they going?

503
00:31:57,549 --> 00:31:59,651
They all need a good whipping
if you ask me.

504
00:31:59,751 --> 00:32:01,720
There's tons of 'em.
I've just seen another lot coming down

505
00:32:01,820 --> 00:32:03,588
from the Ingleby Workhouse
down Broadback Lane.

506
00:32:03,688 --> 00:32:05,257
-Where's that?
-This way!

507
00:32:16,535 --> 00:32:18,603
ROSITA: There's dozens of 'em!

508
00:32:18,703 --> 00:32:20,105
But what for?

509
00:32:55,507 --> 00:32:59,511
You will continue. You will enter
the court of the CyberKing.

510
00:32:59,644 --> 00:33:01,213
(GROWLING)

511
00:33:04,583 --> 00:33:07,185
March. That is an order.

512
00:33:08,420 --> 00:33:09,988
March.

513
00:33:20,832 --> 00:33:22,133
(CRYING)

514
00:33:35,313 --> 00:33:36,715
Where is it?

515
00:33:41,386 --> 00:33:42,787
Where is it?

516
00:33:45,891 --> 00:33:47,425
ROSITA: That's the door to the sluice.

517
00:33:47,526 --> 00:33:49,694
All the sewage runs through there,
straight into the Thames.

518
00:33:49,794 --> 00:33:53,331
Yeah, that's too well-guarded.
We'll have to find another way in.

519
00:33:53,431 --> 00:33:57,802
Oh, that's cheating, sneaking up!
Did you have your legs on silent?

520
00:33:59,070 --> 00:34:01,373
So, what do we have here?

521
00:34:01,473 --> 00:34:03,208
Listen, listen,
just walk towards me slowly.

522
00:34:03,308 --> 00:34:04,342
Don't let them touch you.

523
00:34:04,442 --> 00:34:07,746
Oh, but they wouldn't hurt me,
my fine boys.

524
00:34:07,846 --> 00:34:11,383
They are my knights in shining arm our.
Quite literally.

525
00:34:11,483 --> 00:34:14,085
Even if they've converted you,
that's not a Cyber-speech pattern.

526
00:34:14,185 --> 00:34:16,555
You've still got free will.
I'm telling you, step away!

527
00:34:16,655 --> 00:34:18,623
There's been no conversion, sir.

528
00:34:18,723 --> 00:34:20,825
No one's ever been
able to change my mind.

529
00:34:20,926 --> 00:34:25,030
The Cybermen offered me
the one thing I wanted. Liberation.

530
00:34:25,130 --> 00:34:26,364
Who are you?

531
00:34:26,464 --> 00:34:29,868
You can be quiet.
I doubt he paid you to talk.

532
00:34:29,968 --> 00:34:32,003
More importantly, who are you, sir,

533
00:34:32,103 --> 00:34:34,372
with such intimate knowledge
of my companions?

534
00:34:34,472 --> 00:34:35,574
I'm the Doctor.

535
00:34:35,674 --> 00:34:39,444
Incorrect. You do not correspond
to our image of the Doctor.

536
00:34:39,844 --> 00:34:43,315
Yeah, that's 'cause your database
got corrupted. Oh, look, look, look.

537
00:34:43,381 --> 00:34:44,583
Check this.

538
00:34:44,683 --> 00:34:46,651
The Doctor's info stamp.

539
00:34:48,053 --> 00:34:49,921
Plug it in. Go on, download.

540
00:34:50,021 --> 00:34:54,960
The core has been damaged.
This info stamp would damage cyberunits.

541
00:34:55,060 --> 00:34:56,461
Oh, well. Nice try.

542
00:34:56,528 --> 00:34:57,729
(BEEPING)

543
00:34:57,829 --> 00:34:59,864
Core repaired. Download.

544
00:35:10,275 --> 00:35:11,710
You are the Doctor.

545
00:35:11,810 --> 00:35:13,745
-Hello.
-You will be deleted.

546
00:35:13,845 --> 00:35:14,913
(STUTTERING)

547
00:35:15,013 --> 00:35:16,748
But let me die happy!
Just tell me one thing.

548
00:35:16,848 --> 00:35:18,183
What do you need those children for?

549
00:35:18,283 --> 00:35:21,286
What are children ever needed for?
They're a workforce.

550
00:35:21,386 --> 00:35:22,387
But for what?

551
00:35:22,487 --> 00:35:24,723
Very soon now,
the whole empire will see.

552
00:35:24,823 --> 00:35:26,992
And they will bow down in worship.

553
00:35:27,092 --> 00:35:28,827
And it's all been timed
for Christmas Day.

554
00:35:28,927 --> 00:35:30,195
Was that your idea, Miss...

555
00:35:30,295 --> 00:35:33,865
Hartigan. And yes, it's the perfect
day for a birth,

556
00:35:33,965 --> 00:35:36,034
with a new message for the people.

557
00:35:36,134 --> 00:35:38,403
Only this time, it won't be
the words of a man.

558
00:35:38,503 --> 00:35:40,105
The birth of what?

559
00:35:40,205 --> 00:35:42,941
A birth and a death. Namely yours.

560
00:35:43,575 --> 00:35:45,810
Thank you, Doctor.
Glad to have been part

561
00:35:45,910 --> 00:35:48,480
of your very last conversation.

562
00:35:48,580 --> 00:35:50,382
Now, delete them.

563
00:35:50,882 --> 00:35:52,183
Delete.

564
00:36:06,097 --> 00:36:07,532
At your service, Doctor.

565
00:36:07,632 --> 00:36:09,634
Shades. Shades!

566
00:36:10,001 --> 00:36:11,703
-Run! Come on!
-HARTIGAN: Shades!

567
00:36:11,803 --> 00:36:13,304
One last thing.

568
00:36:14,539 --> 00:36:17,008
Oh, can I say, I completely disapprove!
Come on!

569
00:36:17,108 --> 00:36:19,444
Get off me! I said get off!

570
00:36:19,544 --> 00:36:20,812
(GROWLING)

571
00:36:20,912 --> 00:36:22,280
Tell your masters

572
00:36:22,380 --> 00:36:26,384
we're not waiting till dawn.
The CyberKing will rise

573
00:36:28,486 --> 00:36:29,854
tonight.

574
00:36:32,857 --> 00:36:35,026
That stronghold down by the river.
I need to find a way in.

575
00:36:35,126 --> 00:36:37,796
Now I'm ahead of you.
My wife and I were moving to London

576
00:36:37,896 --> 00:36:39,864
so that I could take up a post
at the university.

577
00:36:39,964 --> 00:36:44,402
And while my memory is still not intact,
this was in the luggage.

578
00:36:45,136 --> 00:36:49,841
The deeds. 15 Latimer Street.
And if I discovered Cybermen there

579
00:36:49,941 --> 00:36:52,243
-in the cellar, then...
-That might be a way in. Brilliant.

580
00:36:52,343 --> 00:36:55,380
But there's still more.
I remember the cellar.

581
00:36:56,214 --> 00:36:57,482
And my wife.

582
00:36:57,816 --> 00:36:59,017
(SCREAMING)

583
00:37:00,285 --> 00:37:03,054
But I swear there was something else
in that room.

584
00:37:07,392 --> 00:37:10,128
If we can find that,
perhaps that's the key

585
00:37:10,228 --> 00:37:13,631
to defeating these invaders. So onwards.

586
00:37:14,265 --> 00:37:15,934
-Maybe you should go back...
-Don't even try!

587
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:17,202
No...

588
00:37:17,902 --> 00:37:21,306
You have wisdom. If the Doctor
is planning to intervene,

589
00:37:21,406 --> 00:37:24,242
then the Ascension
will commence immediately.

590
00:37:24,342 --> 00:37:25,710
Excellent.

591
00:37:26,111 --> 00:37:30,048
And as for you, Mr Cole,
Mr Scoones, Mr Fetch and Mr Milligan,

592
00:37:31,049 --> 00:37:33,418
your work is done.

593
00:37:48,700 --> 00:37:49,968
Children!

594
00:37:50,568 --> 00:37:52,137
Pay attention.

595
00:37:52,737 --> 00:37:56,040
Now let the new
Industrial Revolution begin.

596
00:37:56,541 --> 00:37:58,576
I want to see you work!

597
00:38:30,408 --> 00:38:33,745
Energy levels 60% and rising.

598
00:38:34,245 --> 00:38:36,848
Soon the CyberKing will awake.

599
00:38:37,282 --> 00:38:38,783
Then show me.

600
00:38:46,491 --> 00:38:47,859
Delete.

601
00:38:53,498 --> 00:38:56,634
Must've been guarding this.
A dimension vault.

602
00:38:56,734 --> 00:38:59,604
Stolen from the Daleks again. That's how
the Cybermen travelled through time.

603
00:38:59,704 --> 00:39:02,440
Jackson, is this it?
The thing you couldn't remember?

604
00:39:02,540 --> 00:39:04,175
I don't think so.

605
00:39:04,776 --> 00:39:07,412
I just can't see. It's like it's hidden.

606
00:39:07,512 --> 00:39:10,381
Yeah, not enough power. Come on! Avanti!

607
00:39:14,252 --> 00:39:16,387
Oh, that is magnificent.

608
00:39:20,225 --> 00:39:22,360
That is royalty indeed.

609
00:39:22,527 --> 00:39:25,763
And that's quite a throne.
Oh, you will look resplendent.

610
00:39:25,864 --> 00:39:29,801
The chair you designate as throne
ls not intended for me.

611
00:39:29,901 --> 00:39:34,672
My function is to serve the CyberKing,
not to become the CyberKing.

612
00:39:34,973 --> 00:39:36,741
Then who sits there?

613
00:39:42,647 --> 00:39:45,984
No! Now, just...
I think if you remember correctly,

614
00:39:46,084 --> 00:39:47,585
you said I was to be heralded.

615
00:39:47,685 --> 00:39:49,888
All hail the CyberKing.

616
00:39:49,988 --> 00:39:51,823
CYBERMEN: All hail the CyberKing.

617
00:39:51,923 --> 00:39:54,158
But you promised me.
You said I would never be converted!

618
00:39:54,259 --> 00:39:56,461
That was designated a lie.

619
00:39:57,028 --> 00:39:58,363
What do the Cybermen want?

620
00:39:58,463 --> 00:40:02,567
They want us. That's what Cybermen are,
human beings with their brains

621
00:40:02,667 --> 00:40:06,771
put into metal shells. They want
every living thing to be like them.

622
00:40:06,871 --> 00:40:09,140
You can't do this to me!

623
00:40:09,240 --> 00:40:11,309
Incorrect. It is done.

624
00:40:11,809 --> 00:40:13,745
But I would have served you anyway!

625
00:40:13,845 --> 00:40:17,548
Your mind is riven with anger
and abuse and revenge.

626
00:40:17,649 --> 00:40:21,452
These have no place
in a cybermind. Activate.

627
00:40:23,888 --> 00:40:27,025
Emotions have tormented you
all of your life.

628
00:40:27,125 --> 00:40:31,429
Now you will be set free.
This is your liberation.

629
00:40:31,529 --> 00:40:34,465
Oh, for the love of God!
Have you no pity?

630
00:40:35,166 --> 00:40:36,501
Correct.

631
00:40:46,044 --> 00:40:48,246
The CyberKing is born.

632
00:40:48,379 --> 00:40:50,448
CYBERMEN: All the hail the CyberKing.

633
00:41:12,303 --> 00:41:13,404
Upon my soul...

634
00:41:13,504 --> 00:41:15,139
What is it?

635
00:41:15,239 --> 00:41:16,808
It's an engine.

636
00:41:29,220 --> 00:41:31,923
They're generating electricity.
But what for?

637
00:41:32,023 --> 00:41:33,391
We can set them free.

638
00:41:33,491 --> 00:41:35,326
No, no, no, no, no.

639
00:41:41,299 --> 00:41:42,367
(SIGHING)

640
00:41:43,468 --> 00:41:46,971
I hold such information/

641
00:41:50,708 --> 00:41:52,110
Power at 90%.

642
00:41:52,210 --> 00:41:53,711
But if we stop the engine,
the power dies down,

643
00:41:53,811 --> 00:41:56,247
and the Cybermen will come running. Ooh.

644
00:41:56,748 --> 00:41:59,550
Hold on. Power fluctuation.
That's not meant to happen.

645
00:41:59,650 --> 00:42:00,918
It's going wrong?

646
00:42:01,019 --> 00:42:06,290
No, it's weird. The software's
rewriting itself. It's changing.

647
00:42:06,991 --> 00:42:10,228
I can see the stars. The worlds beyond.

648
00:42:10,528 --> 00:42:14,565
The vortex of time itself
and the whole of infinity.

649
00:42:14,665 --> 00:42:16,467
Oh, but this is glorious!

650
00:42:16,567 --> 00:42:20,038
That is incorrect. "Glorious" is
an emotional response.

651
00:42:20,138 --> 00:42:23,608
Exactly. There is so much joy
in this machine.

652
00:42:23,708 --> 00:42:25,676
Joy is not acceptable.

653
00:42:25,777 --> 00:42:29,514
Don't you see? My mind is stronger
than you ever thought.

654
00:42:29,614 --> 00:42:32,884
It dominates, sir! It dominates you!

655
00:42:32,984 --> 00:42:36,120
Alert. You are operating beyond
the standard parameters.

656
00:42:36,220 --> 00:42:39,390
I am new.
The might of your technology combined

657
00:42:39,490 --> 00:42:42,026
with my own imagination. Yes!

658
00:42:42,693 --> 00:42:44,996
There will be a new race of Cybermen.

659
00:42:45,096 --> 00:42:50,435
My Cybermen. Logic and strength
combined with fury and passion.

660
00:42:50,535 --> 00:42:54,772
Diagnosis, system failure.
You will be removed from the processor.

661
00:43:02,647 --> 00:43:05,550
Whoa! What the hell is happening?
It's out of control!

662
00:43:05,650 --> 00:43:08,286
It's accelerating. 96%, 97...

663
00:43:08,386 --> 00:43:11,155
When it reaches 100,
what about the children?

664
00:43:11,255 --> 00:43:13,458
They're disposable. Come on!

665
00:43:16,494 --> 00:43:18,563
I am CyberKing.

666
00:43:18,930 --> 00:43:21,666
My mind inside the Cybermen.

667
00:43:22,366 --> 00:43:24,168
And you will obey me.

668
00:43:24,268 --> 00:43:27,038
CYBERMEN: All hail the CyberKing!

669
00:43:28,639 --> 00:43:30,908
Power levels now at 100%.

670
00:43:31,008 --> 00:43:32,810
Delete the workforce.

671
00:43:32,910 --> 00:43:34,579
(ALARM BLARING)

672
00:43:34,645 --> 00:43:35,780
Delete.

673
00:43:37,281 --> 00:43:38,449
Delete.

674
00:43:39,484 --> 00:43:40,618
Delete.

675
00:43:41,686 --> 00:43:46,057
DOCTOR: Right, now, all of you, out!
Do you hear me? That's an order!

676
00:43:46,524 --> 00:43:48,593
Every single one of you, run!

677
00:43:48,693 --> 00:43:51,596
All of you, come on!
As fast as you can! Come on!

678
00:43:51,696 --> 00:43:53,965
There's a hot pie for everyone
if you leg it!

679
00:43:54,065 --> 00:43:55,099
Go!

680
00:43:55,199 --> 00:43:57,702
Rosita, get them out of the sluice gate!
Once you're out, keep running!

681
00:43:57,802 --> 00:44:00,104
Far as you can!

682
00:44:01,172 --> 00:44:03,441
Come on. Come on. Come on.

683
00:44:09,280 --> 00:44:11,782
Turn right at the corner!
Fast as you can!

684
00:44:11,883 --> 00:44:13,184
And don't stop!

685
00:44:13,284 --> 00:44:15,386
Keep running! Keep running!

686
00:44:15,887 --> 00:44:18,322
Come, my soldiers. Come to me.

687
00:44:23,361 --> 00:44:25,663
Come on, run!

688
00:44:25,763 --> 00:44:27,865
Quick! Keep running! Keep running!

689
00:44:35,173 --> 00:44:37,241
Go! Quick! Quick!

690
00:44:39,443 --> 00:44:42,680
DOCTOR: It's some sort of starter motor,
but starting what?

691
00:44:59,297 --> 00:45:00,731
(SCREAMING)

692
00:45:00,798 --> 00:45:02,567
CAROLINE: No!

693
00:45:06,737 --> 00:45:08,306
Help!

694
00:45:12,944 --> 00:45:15,346
Father!

695
00:45:20,518 --> 00:45:22,486
Father!

696
00:45:22,720 --> 00:45:24,222
Father!

697
00:45:24,322 --> 00:45:25,690
That's my son.

698
00:45:28,292 --> 00:45:29,460
My son.

699
00:45:30,228 --> 00:45:32,597
-Doctor, my son!
-What?

700
00:45:32,697 --> 00:45:35,433
They took my son.
No wonder my mind escaped.

701
00:45:35,533 --> 00:45:38,903
Those damned Cybermen, they took
my child! But he's alive, Doctor.

702
00:45:39,003 --> 00:45:41,172
-Frederic!
-Come on!

703
00:45:41,539 --> 00:45:45,810
Oh, he's too scared. Stay there.
Don't move! I'm coming!

704
00:45:47,612 --> 00:45:50,014
CyberKing rising.

705
00:45:57,488 --> 00:45:59,323
I can't get up there! Fred!

706
00:45:59,423 --> 00:46:01,325
DOCTOR: They've finished with the motor.
It's gonna blow up!

707
00:46:01,425 --> 00:46:03,461
What are we gonna do, Doctor?
What are we gonna do?

708
00:46:03,561 --> 00:46:05,196
Come on, Jackson.

709
00:46:09,267 --> 00:46:10,668
You know me.

710
00:46:16,941 --> 00:46:18,843
Oh, that's it! Hello!

711
00:46:18,943 --> 00:46:21,545
Now, hold on tight. Don't let go.

712
00:46:45,136 --> 00:46:46,771
Merry Christmas.

713
00:46:47,605 --> 00:46:49,507
Oh!

714
00:46:51,842 --> 00:46:55,846
Go to St Stephen's, ask for the warden.
He'll take care of you.

715
00:46:55,946 --> 00:46:57,748
Now, run! Quickly!

716
00:47:09,160 --> 00:47:11,395
(CHILDREN SCREAMING)

717
00:47:11,495 --> 00:47:15,099
It's under the water!
There's something in the Thames!

718
00:47:25,443 --> 00:47:27,211
DOCTOR: Head for the street!

719
00:47:29,847 --> 00:47:32,817
-JACKSON: Come on, Doctor, hurry up.
-Gotcha!

720
00:47:37,855 --> 00:47:40,091
Behold! I am risen.

721
00:47:40,825 --> 00:47:44,862
Witness me, mankind,
as CyberKing of all.

722
00:47:47,898 --> 00:47:51,068
-It's a CyberKing!
-And a CyberKing is what?

723
00:47:51,168 --> 00:47:54,071
It's a ship. Dreadnought class.
Front line of an invasion,

724
00:47:54,171 --> 00:47:58,542
and inside the chest, a cyberfactory,
ready to convert millions!

725
00:47:58,642 --> 00:48:00,511
And I will walk.

726
00:48:00,611 --> 00:48:05,449
I will stride
across this tiny little world!

727
00:48:08,586 --> 00:48:10,287
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

728
00:48:20,698 --> 00:48:22,099
My people.

729
00:48:23,167 --> 00:48:25,403
Why do they not rejoice?

730
00:48:33,611 --> 00:48:35,880
Just head south. Take him south!
Go to the parkland!

731
00:48:35,980 --> 00:48:37,281
-But where are you going?
-To stop that thing.

732
00:48:37,381 --> 00:48:38,549
Then I should be with you.

733
00:48:38,649 --> 00:48:41,285
Jackson, you've got your son.
You've got a reason to live.

734
00:48:41,385 --> 00:48:42,987
And you haven't?

735
00:48:46,824 --> 00:48:48,826
God save you, Doctor.

736
00:49:06,143 --> 00:49:08,345
What the hell is that thing, sir?

737
00:49:08,446 --> 00:49:11,615
Oh, good man! Jed, wasn't it?
Jed, I need your help!

738
00:49:11,715 --> 00:49:13,117
I'm not going out there!

739
00:49:13,217 --> 00:49:15,486
I'll give you five pound notes.

740
00:49:15,853 --> 00:49:18,589
Um...
All right. What do you want me to do?

741
00:49:18,689 --> 00:49:20,825
The Tardis is gonna fly!

742
00:49:27,731 --> 00:49:30,134
People of the world, now hear me.

743
00:49:30,935 --> 00:49:33,437
Your governments will surrender.

744
00:49:34,638 --> 00:49:38,142
And if not, then behold my power!

745
00:49:58,929 --> 00:50:02,099
-You're flamin' bonkers, you are, sir!
-It's been said before! Now, give me!

746
00:50:02,199 --> 00:50:05,169
Not enough power. Come on!
Jed, let her loose!

747
00:50:06,904 --> 00:50:10,007
-Ever flown one of these before?
-Nope, never!

748
00:50:11,442 --> 00:50:14,078
-Can I have my money now?
-Oh, get on with it!

749
00:50:15,246 --> 00:50:17,014
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

750
00:50:19,783 --> 00:50:23,721
-But, sir, I thought I'd lost you.
-My son, Rosita. This boy is my son.

751
00:50:40,204 --> 00:50:42,239
God's luck to you, sir!

752
00:50:42,339 --> 00:50:44,008
(JED LAUGHING)

753
00:50:49,580 --> 00:50:51,048
It's the Tardis.

754
00:50:51,649 --> 00:50:53,083
She's flying!

755
00:51:05,329 --> 00:51:07,197
Who the hell is that?

756
00:51:07,298 --> 00:51:08,599
His name, sir,

757
00:51:10,200 --> 00:51:11,802
is the Doctor.

758
00:51:18,842 --> 00:51:20,077
(ALARM BLARING)

759
00:51:20,177 --> 00:51:22,446
Attention. Proximity alert.

760
00:51:22,546 --> 00:51:24,682
How is that even possible?

761
00:51:24,782 --> 00:51:27,384
Oh, this I would see. Turn!

762
00:51:44,702 --> 00:51:47,171
Excellent. The Doctor.

763
00:51:47,404 --> 00:51:50,841
Yet another man come to assert
himself against me in the night.

764
00:51:50,941 --> 00:51:53,844
Miss Hartigan,
I'm offering you a choice.

765
00:51:54,478 --> 00:51:58,549
You might have the most remarkable mind
this world has ever seen.

766
00:51:58,649 --> 00:52:01,185
Strong enough to control
the Cybermen themselves!

767
00:52:01,285 --> 00:52:03,420
I don't need you to sanction me.

768
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:06,457
No, but such a mind deserves to live.

769
00:52:06,557 --> 00:52:09,860
The Cybermen came to this world
using a dimension vault.

770
00:52:09,960 --> 00:52:14,398
I can use that device to find you
a home. With no people to convert.

771
00:52:14,498 --> 00:52:19,136
But a new world where you can live out
your mechanical life in peace.

772
00:52:19,236 --> 00:52:23,240
I have the world below
and it is abundant with so many minds

773
00:52:23,340 --> 00:52:27,077
ready to become extensions of me,
why would I leave this place?

774
00:52:27,177 --> 00:52:30,214
Because if you don't,
I'll have to stop you.

775
00:52:30,981 --> 00:52:34,218
What do you make of me, sir? An idiot?

776
00:52:34,284 --> 00:52:35,552
No.

777
00:52:36,453 --> 00:52:39,023
The question is, what do you make of me?

778
00:52:43,861 --> 00:52:45,362
Destroy him!

779
00:52:45,496 --> 00:52:47,498
You make me into this.

780
00:53:05,182 --> 00:53:07,217
Then I have made you a failure.

781
00:53:07,317 --> 00:53:09,653
Your weapons are useless, sir.

782
00:53:09,753 --> 00:53:12,423
I wasn't trying to kill you.

783
00:53:12,523 --> 00:53:15,392
All I did was break the cyberconnection,

784
00:53:16,260 --> 00:53:18,262
leaving your mind open.

785
00:53:19,329 --> 00:53:24,034
Open, I think, for the first time
in far too many years,

786
00:53:25,202 --> 00:53:26,503
SO you can see.

787
00:53:26,603 --> 00:53:28,038
(HARTIGAN GASPING)

788
00:53:28,138 --> 00:53:30,107
Just look at yourself.

789
00:53:30,207 --> 00:53:32,209
Look at what you've done!

790
00:53:33,143 --> 00:53:35,512
I'm sorry, Miss Hartigan,

791
00:53:35,612 --> 00:53:38,015
but look at what you've become.

792
00:53:39,216 --> 00:53:40,818
(SCREAMING)

793
00:53:43,520 --> 00:53:45,055
I'm so sorry.

794
00:53:47,224 --> 00:53:50,094
(PIERCING SCREAM)

795
00:54:01,872 --> 00:54:03,073
He's killed it!

796
00:54:03,173 --> 00:54:05,576
Whatever he did, he's killed it!

797
00:54:09,079 --> 00:54:10,581
But it's gonna fall!

798
00:54:10,681 --> 00:54:12,316
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

799
00:54:31,635 --> 00:54:32,970
(BEEPING)

800
00:54:33,971 --> 00:54:35,572
Now you're ready.

801
00:55:03,400 --> 00:55:04,802
Well,

802
00:55:06,336 --> 00:55:08,338
I'd say he used
that dimension vault to transfer

803
00:55:08,438 --> 00:55:10,941
the wreckage of the CyberKing
into the time vortex,

804
00:55:11,041 --> 00:55:13,510
there to be harmlessly disintegrated.

805
00:55:13,610 --> 00:55:16,380
(CHUCKLING) Oh, I've picked up a lot.

806
00:55:16,446 --> 00:55:18,182
Ah, but here.

807
00:55:18,282 --> 00:55:21,718
Ladies and gentlemen, I know that man!

808
00:55:22,152 --> 00:55:23,921
That Doctor on high!

809
00:55:24,021 --> 00:55:27,825
And I know that he has done this deed
1,000 times.

810
00:55:27,925 --> 00:55:32,863
But not once, no, sir, not once,
not ever has he ever been thanked.

811
00:55:32,963 --> 00:55:39,136
But no more, for I say to you
on this Christmas Morn, bravo, sir!

812
00:55:39,603 --> 00:55:40,704
Bravo!

813
00:55:40,804 --> 00:55:42,573
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

814
00:55:45,175 --> 00:55:46,944
JACKSON: Bravo, sir!

815
00:55:56,353 --> 00:55:57,754
Bravo, sir!

816
00:56:12,703 --> 00:56:14,238
Bravo, Doctor.

817
00:56:26,783 --> 00:56:29,853
JACKSON: The city will recover.
As London always does.

818
00:56:31,455 --> 00:56:33,390
Though the events
of today will be history,

819
00:56:33,490 --> 00:56:37,361
-spoken of for centuries to come.
-Yeah. Funny that.

820
00:56:38,562 --> 00:56:41,465
JACKSON: And a new history
begins for me.

821
00:56:41,565 --> 00:56:44,568
I find myself a widower,
but with my son,

822
00:56:44,701 --> 00:56:46,603
and with a good friend.

823
00:56:46,703 --> 00:56:49,706
Now, take care of that one.
She's marvellous.

824
00:56:49,806 --> 00:56:53,610
Frederic will need a nursemaid
and I can think of none better.

825
00:56:55,612 --> 00:56:59,283
But you're welcome to join us.
We thought we might all dine together

826
00:56:59,383 --> 00:57:01,218
at the Traveller's Halt,

827
00:57:01,852 --> 00:57:04,254
a Christmas feast in celebration,

828
00:57:06,523 --> 00:57:09,059
and in memory of those we have lost.

829
00:57:12,763 --> 00:57:14,298
You won't stay.

830
00:57:15,966 --> 00:57:18,101
Like I said, you know me.

831
00:57:19,636 --> 00:57:20,737
No,

832
00:57:22,172 --> 00:57:24,074
I don't think anyone does.

833
00:57:25,475 --> 00:57:27,678
Oh! And this is it!

834
00:57:28,078 --> 00:57:29,146
Oh!

835
00:57:29,246 --> 00:57:32,282
Oh, if I might, Doctor,
one last adventure?

836
00:57:32,382 --> 00:57:33,617
Oh.

837
00:57:33,717 --> 00:57:35,252
Be my guest.

838
00:57:40,357 --> 00:57:41,658
Oh!

839
00:57:45,495 --> 00:57:46,897
Oh, my word.

840
00:57:47,931 --> 00:57:49,232
Oh!

841
00:57:49,766 --> 00:57:51,969
Oh, goodness me.

842
00:57:53,770 --> 00:57:55,038
(CHUCKLING)

843
00:57:55,138 --> 00:57:56,606
But this is...

844
00:57:58,375 --> 00:58:00,110
This is nonsense!

845
00:58:01,078 --> 00:58:03,113
Well, that's one word for it.

846
00:58:04,047 --> 00:58:06,683
Complete and utter, wonderful nonsense!

847
00:58:07,751 --> 00:58:09,619
How very, very silly!

848
00:58:11,121 --> 00:58:15,258
Oh, no, I can't bear it.
Oh, it's causing my head to ache.

849
00:58:15,359 --> 00:58:17,127
No, no, no, no, no!

850
00:58:18,128 --> 00:58:19,963
Oh! Oh, gracious!

851
00:58:21,298 --> 00:58:23,000
That's quite enough.

852
00:58:28,572 --> 00:58:30,607
I take it this is goodbye.

853
00:58:31,174 --> 00:58:32,809
Onwards and upwards.

854
00:58:32,909 --> 00:58:34,811
But tell me one thing.

855
00:58:34,911 --> 00:58:37,214
All those facts and figures I saw
of the Doctor's life,

856
00:58:37,314 --> 00:58:39,082
you were never alone.

857
00:58:39,182 --> 00:58:41,852
All those bright and shining companions.

858
00:58:42,519 --> 00:58:44,454
But not any more?

859
00:58:44,521 --> 00:58:45,856
No.

860
00:58:45,956 --> 00:58:47,591
Might I ask why not?

861
00:58:47,691 --> 00:58:48,992
They leave.

862
00:58:50,694 --> 00:58:53,630
Because they should,
or they find someone else.

863
00:58:55,298 --> 00:58:58,301
And some of them... Some of them

864
00:58:58,368 --> 00:58:59,669
forget me.

865
00:59:01,872 --> 00:59:03,673
I suppose, in the end,

866
00:59:10,013 --> 00:59:11,782
they break my heart.

867
00:59:16,319 --> 00:59:18,221
That offer of Christmas dinner,

868
00:59:18,321 --> 00:59:21,258
it's no longer a request, it's a demand.

869
00:59:22,059 --> 00:59:24,361
In memory of those we've lost.

870
00:59:27,798 --> 00:59:30,133
Oh, go on, then.

871
00:59:30,233 --> 00:59:31,535
-Really?
-Just this once.

872
00:59:31,635 --> 00:59:33,737
You've actually gone
and changed my mind.

873
00:59:33,837 --> 00:59:36,006
And not many people can do that.

874
00:59:36,073 --> 00:59:37,407
Jackson,

875
00:59:38,041 --> 00:59:41,111
if anyone had to be the Doctor,
I'm glad it was you.

876
00:59:41,211 --> 00:59:44,281
The feast awaits. Come with me.

877
00:59:44,381 --> 00:59:46,049
-Walk this way.
-I certainly will!

878
00:59:46,149 --> 00:59:47,617
(JACKSON CHUCKLING)

879
00:59:47,717 --> 00:59:50,020
Merry Christmas to you, Jackson.

880
00:59:50,120 --> 00:59:52,389
Merry Christmas indeed, Doctor.

